composition: Metallurgy - Analyst: BM Res. Lab - Craddock; Bibliog: File 4532; Composition: CU 66.5; Pb 21.6; Sn 8.2; AS 1.5; Sb 0.23; Bi 0.8; Ni 0.24; Ag 0.06; Co 0.014; Zn 0.02; Fe 0.03
associations: 8a. Single Find
description: Dimensions: max dimension 69.0mm; EL tube possibly full L 43.5; B tube (middle) 24.7; Wt. 186.8g,Typology: craggy lump of bronze incorporating half-melted implements: (1) tube with flanged opening on one side at presumed centre, and tube here a little swollen with rounded ridge encircling and continuing onto flange to give very slightly lentrical shape to opening; edge of flange not a regular shape in profile and pres. broken, but surface more smooth; more intact end of tube with slight expansion to ridge and outer bevelled perimeter; basically amorphous lump protruding from this end, may be part of an original rod-like extension; side opening is blocked just below level of tube surface-apparently continuous casting, no crack apparent. (2) short stretch of curved rod of eye-shaped section; length of 13mm of concave face exposed before swallowed by lump; outer face concealed; outer end very rounded - looks most like runner of casting jet, more elliptical than known fleshhook prongs. (3) 'strip' in edge of lump EL 15mm, T 1.5-2.5 - apparently a little twisted along length W of end exposed on face (1) 7.3. (4) 'strip' - with 3 apparent mouldings on exposed face - parallel; EL 10.8; W 9.5 (5) A few other small projections - more amorphous and uncertain whether parts of object.
remarks: PIF; DF(S); SI; RSO 29/5/79; CI; Rec.: SN Aug. 80; Source: Sb. A.; Sub. Inf.: D.T.D. Clarke, Colchester Mus. 23 May 79; Cont. Card. 1

site: England,Shropshire,Little Wenlock,Willow Moor,(Alias Wrekin Tenement, 1834, Dukes),1835
toSearch: Little Wenlock, Telford, Telford And Wrekin Tf6, UK
patina: Dull rusty brown and grey green
other: Width: blade 34mm; 41mm; Socket 25.5mm,Thickness: blade 12mm; socket 25.5mm,Weight: 70.88 gms
associations: Part of a hoard
description: Badly damaged. Very thin metal. Socket about 1/4mm thick. 2 Rivet holes. Mr. Pritchard writes to L.F. Chitty 31.10.23: "The 3 broken spearheads (bronze) were found in 1835 during excavations in connection with drainage of Willow Moor Farm. Of course the finder is dead, also his son who kept them in memory of his father; I knew the son casually but can not find out his name. I have no reason to doubt the authenticity of the specimens. Along with the bronze spearheads was found a stone celt (Knife LFC) also in my possession."
publications: As. Wrekin Tenement 1834, T.F. Dukes, Nov. 20, 1834, in Arch XXVI, 464-5.,Brief mentions in Arch. Camb. III (4th S), 338, + Montgom. Collection III, 437,As "Willow Morr. Willow Farm, or Wrekin Farm, 1835", Hartshorne, Salopia Antiqua (1841); Arch Jour. VIII (1851) 197.; Shrops. Arch. Trans. IV (2) 279. "Wrekin Farm" but pp. 89-98 + plate quoting Evans "Wrekin Tenement", as "Near Little Wenlock" or "Little Wenlock, Stop" (error amended later). Evans B. Imps (Hoard No. 44) pp. 44, 113, 234, 314, 336, 452, 461, 465. He recognised that this was "possibly the same hoard as No. 41 (Wrekin Tenement)". That these two hoards are identical is proved by the same spearhead with limited openings + socketed celt with a notch chipped in the edge, or curving in each.  Anden, Vic. Co. Hist. Shrops. I, 203.

surface: light brown, considerably scratched, golden bronze shows.
associations: A hoard "lying together in a heap, cupable of being covered by a 1/2 bushel measure " consisting of this celt", a small number of Swords, a about 150 fragments of javelins, or spear-heads, with staves of decayed wood fastened in several of them." (Dukes, Arch.XXVI, 464-5, under "Wrekin Tenement.") Hartshorne, under "Willow Moor", gives "2-300" broken spears, 3 or 4 small Whetstones, a celt & a blade & handle of a dagger, broken, found near tumuli.
description: Decoration much worn. Cast marks.
publications: Arch. xxvi, 464-5; Arch. Jo. viii, 197, R. Lloyd Kenyon, Shrops. Arch. Trans. IV (2nd S.) 279.,  Hartshorne, Salop, Ant. pp. 89-98., Audin, Vic. Co. Hist. Shrops. I, 203., Evans, Anc. Br. Imps., under "Little Wenlock" pp. 113, 234, 314, 336, 452, 465; "Wrekin Tenement", 285, 338, 465.
remarks: Shrewsbury Museum Donations Book I records that on Oct. 1835, T.F. Dukes, Esq. presented a celt found near the Wrekin & a cast from a spearhead found at the same place in 1834. The latter is identical with that given to the Society of Antiquaries & with the specimen figured by Rev. G.H. Hartshorne, "Salopia Antiqua" (1841), pl. facing p. 96, N¬∞ 8 described with the Willow Moor, Willow Farm, or Wrekin Farm, hoard, in the parish of Little Wenlock, stated, however, to have been found in 1835. Hartshorne's figure of this celt shows no ornament, but the lines in the actual object are faint.

description: Dimensions: EL 101.5mm; EWe 36; W shoulders 28.4; Wm 32; Bm 32.5; max B loop 8.1; Ds 60.5; Wt. 148.9 g,Typology: triple m.m., lower 2 tend to become one on rev. face; prominent ribs define wing-indentations; body angles above are rounded, below - very square; ribs contrive as slight bumps across sides emphasising shoulders; good rect. socket. with rect. flat end, tapering all down; prominent ribs on int. faces for about 2/3 length.,Manufacture: top of m. flattened, some hmks., but still suggestion of linear edge of loop side; medium thick cg. fl. .along upper sides quite prom. - crest flat to rounded - prob. some minimal hammering - some waivering, and rev. are asymmetric; cg. gl. totally removed on lower sides; two uppermost bevels on bl. faces prob. entirely forged, creating shallow furrow between; another lower more diffuse and amidst hmks.; cmks criss-crossing on bl. e. - mainly soil filled - prob. anc.; sub-triang. hollow below shoulder on rev. side - cg. flaw or chaplet? series of v. fine. pmks. on indented sides - not obviously decoration; occasional larger ones; depression at corner of mouth likely cg. flaw.,Condition: cutting edge completely list due to fracture - due to poor state of metal, apparently found with edge intact and only tips broken off.,Attached Material: Yellowy fawn soil coating socket.
publications: a) notes made on submission by RPJ,b) information passed over telephone 2/7/80 to SN

other: Length: 22.5 in. = 571.5mm,Width: 1.75 in = 44.45mm (just below hilt),Thickness: 0.3 in. = 7.62mm (just below hilt)
description: Leaf shaped blade and straight shoulders, slight swelling in outline of grip, widest part nearest shoulder. Two rivet holes on one shoulder, but metal broken away on other shoulder at rivet holes. One rivet hole in hilt set i longitudinal groove; within same groove a dimple (mid-way between hole and widening for shoulder) perhaps for another hole which had not been perforated. The groove forks below dimple, but is deeper on side of surviving shoulder rivet holes. At junction of hilt and shoulder side pressure has pressed edges up slightly. Blade, an elongated oval, broken at 9.4 in. (238.76mm) from tip: pieces fit together. Outer face (.5mm) in many places flaked off, but surviving surface and metal appears stable.
publications: 1. 17th Annual Report of the Warwickshire Natural History and Archaeological Society, April, 1853, p. 3.,2. F. W. Shotton, Proc. Coventry Natural History and Scientific Society, vol. U, 1938, pp. 190 & 191.
